The reason is that if one thread updates `cache`, while another is reading it, the second thread will either see a reference to the old or new instance of `OneValueCache` (this is guaranteed by the volatile variable). And because `OneValueCache` is immutable, is not that the values could change under the rug.

There could be one problem though. Imagine that service calls `getFactors` twice.
```
    public void service(int sec) {
        BigInteger[] one = cache.getFactors(i, sec);
        [...]
        BigInteger[] two = cache.getFactors(i, sec);
    }
```
In this case the underlying cached value could have changed. If that&#39;s a bad thing, the code could first assign `cache` to a local variable and reference that.

